Biased transmission and transformation in birdsong

Please make sure that you have sensitivity, truncnorm, and data.table installed in RStudio.

#install required packages
install.packages("sensitivity")
install.packages("truncnorm")
install.packages("data.table")

In this workshop we will build an agent-based model of biased transmission and transformation in swamp sparrow song (Melospiza georgiana). Swamp sparrow song is an excellent model of biased transmission and transformation because there is empirical evidence for the following three things:

  1. Transformation: birds increase the trill rates of low-quality songs at the expense of learning accuracy (Lahti et al., 2011).
  2. Selective attrition: birds are less likely to learn songs that are relatively hard to produce, imposing (one of several) upper bounds on trill rate (Podos et al., 2004).
  3. Biased transmission: cultural evolutionary patterns in wild populations are consistent with conformity (Lachlan et al., 2018).

Specifially, we will model how all of these factors influence the recovery of trill rate after a population crash has reduced the cultural diversity of a population. Let’s get started!

Modeling transformation

First let’s take a look at how Hudson and Creanza (2022) modeled cultural transformation in birdsong using a modified version of the Price equation first introduced by Henrich (2004). z_max is the current maximum value of a trait in the population—in this case the maximum trill rate of a song type. To get the distribution of possible values for z in the next generation, we would generate a Gumbel distribution centered around z_max - alpha with variance controlled by beta. Let’s try this with z_max of 1, alpha of 0.4, and beta of 0.1, and we’ll truncate the distribution at 0 to prevent negative values.

#set parameters
z_max <- 1
alpha <- 0.4
beta <- 0.1

#generate sequence and get distribution across it
sequence <- seq(0, 1.4, 0.01)
distribution <- sensitivity::dgumbel.trunc(sequence, loc = z_max-alpha, scale = beta, min = 0.0001)

The red vertical line is the current z_max of the population, and the black distribution shows the possible values of z in the next generation. When N birds learn this particular song type, we will sample N values from this distribution and overwrite the current z_max with the largest value. In small populations this means that the trill rate will often decrease, whereas in large populations it will increase. This model assumes that new birds in the population can learn from anybody and use the best possible version of a song type as their target.

Let’s wrap this model in a basic function and iterate it out for 100 timesteps with different values of N to see what happens.

#wrap model in function
sample_z <- function(N, z_max, alpha, beta){
  return(sensitivity::rgumbel.trunc(N, loc = z_max-alpha, scale = beta, min = 0.0001))
}

#simulate a changing song type in a small population of 20
small_pop <- c()
temp_z_max <- 1
for(i in 1:100){
  temp <- sample_z(20, temp_z_max, alpha, beta)
  small_pop <- c(small_pop, median(temp))
  temp_z_max <- max(temp)
}

#simulate a changing song type in a large population of 50
large_pop <- c()
temp_z_max <- 1
for(i in 1:100){
  temp <- sample_z(50, temp_z_max, alpha, beta)
  large_pop <- c(large_pop, median(temp))
  temp_z_max <- max(temp)
}

As expected the trill rate tends to increase when there are enough birds in each generation that at least one has a higher z than the previous z_max. Increasing alpha or reducing beta would slow down the rate of increase, but we’ll stick with the current values for now.

Embedding in random copying model

Now let’s embed this transformation function into a random copying model. This model will simulate birds randomly copying songs from previous generations and slowly improving them over time. The first step is to store all possible songs that can exist in a data table, alongside the parameters for the transformation function with a bit of random jitter. Let’s assume that we have 160 total_types. The price_params object is a vector with the (1) mean z_max, (2) mean alpha, (3) mean beta, and (4) the standard deviation for all three (0.01). This way each song will start out with a slightly different trill rate and probability of improvement.

#set parameters
total_types <- 160
price_params <- c(z_max, alpha, beta, 0.01)

#initialize songs in data table
songs <- data.table::data.table(type = 1:total_types,
                                z_max = truncnorm::rtruncnorm(total_types, a = 0, mean = price_params[1], sd = price_params[4]),
                                alpha = truncnorm::rtruncnorm(total_types, a = 0, mean = price_params[2], sd = price_params[4]),
                                beta = truncnorm::rtruncnorm(total_types, a = 0, mean = price_params[3], sd = price_params[4]))
##      type     z_max     alpha       beta
##   1:    1 1.0064295 0.4011610 0.10951062
##   2:    2 1.0111482 0.4113969 0.10052627
##   3:    3 1.0167328 0.4068914 0.09820731
##   4:    4 0.9995143 0.3906590 0.10622414
##   5:    5 0.9927326 0.4036571 0.12407527
##  ---                                    
## 156:  156 0.9978196 0.3901022 0.09663282
## 157:  157 0.9990255 0.3881940 0.11733124
## 158:  158 1.0060818 0.4000329 0.10329097
## 159:  159 0.9952259 0.4106720 0.09575226
## 160:  160 1.0065929 0.3849578 0.11667594

As you can see, each song type has a numeric ID and slightly different parameters for the sample_z function. Now let’s create a data table where we will store our birds’ repertoires, or the songs that they have learned. Let’s assume that birds have a repertoire size of 10 songs, and that at the beginning of the model there are only 20 song types that exist in the population (before innovation happens). Let’s also set N to 200.

#set parameters
N <- 200
init_types <- 20
rep_size <- 10

#initialize birds in data table
birds <- data.table::data.table(rep = lapply(1:N, function(x){sample(init_types, rep_size)}))
##                        rep
##   1:  7, 4,15,18,19,11,...
##   2:  4, 8,17, 9,14, 3,...
##   3: 10, 5,16, 4, 2,12,...
##   4:  3, 1, 9,16,12,11,...
##   5:  5,13, 6,17, 9,14,...
##  ---                      
## 196: 19,12,17,13,18, 5,...
## 197:  1, 7,20,16,12,11,...
## 198: 13,20, 2, 4,11,18,...
## 199:  9,16,11,18, 7, 5,...
## 200: 17,16, 5,11, 4,19,...

Each row corresponds to a bird, and rep contains a vector of song types for each bird.

Now let’s build up our loop that will simulate our generations of birds across the 100 timesteps.

  1. We create an output object to store the median z values in. Then we start our loop.
  2. At the beginning of each timestep we create a frequency table of all of the syllables in the population. Then we collect the median z value across all syllables in the population and add it to our output object.
  3. Once the output is collected, we create a data table of all of the new birds in the population. The number of new birds in the population is determined by N*b_d_rate, where b_d_rate is the birth and death rate of the population. Let’s set b_d_rate to 0.5. For now we fill up each new birds’ repertoire by sampling song types proportional to their frequency in the population.
  4. We simulate innovation. First, we sample new birds to be innovators with probability mu. For each innovator we iterate through their repertoire and replace each song with a random song from the total_types with probability mu. Let’s set mu to 0.2.
  5. Then we simulate transformation using the method described above. For each of the songs that the new birds have learned or innovate, we collect N samples of z with the sample_z function and replace the previous z_max.
  6. Finally, we combined the new birds with the full population and random remove N*b_d_rate birds to simulate overwinter mortality.
#set parameters
timesteps <- 100
b_d_rate <- 0.5
mu <- 0.2

#create output object
output <- list()

#for each timestep
for(i in 1:timesteps){
  #compile frequency table of songs in the population
  freq_table <- table(unlist(birds$rep))
  freq_table <- data.table::data.table(type = as.numeric(names(freq_table)), freq = as.numeric(freq_table), z_max = songs$z_max[as.numeric(names(freq_table))])

  #collect the median z values for each song in the population to output
  output[[i]] <- sapply(freq_table$type, function(x){median(sample_z(z_max = songs$z_max[x], alpha = songs$alpha[x], beta = songs$beta[x], N = N))})

  #new birds are born and learn song types proportional to their frequency in the population
  new_birds <- data.table::data.table(rep = lapply(1:(N*b_d_rate), function(x){sample(freq_table$type, rep_size, prob = freq_table$freq)}))

  #new birds sampled to innovate with probability mu replace song types with another from the total pool of songs with probability mu
  to_innovate <- which(sample(c(TRUE, FALSE), N*b_d_rate, prob = c(mu, 1-mu), replace = TRUE))
  for(j in to_innovate){
    new_rep <- new_birds$rep[[j]]
    num_innovate <- rbinom(1, rep_size, mu)
    new_rep[sample(rep_size, num_innovate)] <- sample(total_types, num_innovate)
    new_birds$rep[[j]] <- new_rep
  }

  #improvement of song types occurs among new birds
  to_improve <- sort(unique(unlist(new_birds$rep)))
  for(j in to_improve){
    new_z_max <- max(sample_z(z_max = songs$z_max[j], alpha = songs$alpha[j], beta = songs$beta[j], N = N*b_d_rate))
    songs$z_max[j] <- new_z_max
  }

  #add new birds to entire population and then simulate mortality
  birds <- data.table::rbindlist(list(birds, new_birds))
  birds <- birds[-sample(N+(N*b_d_rate), N*b_d_rate), ]
}

The output of this is a list, where each entry is the median z value for each of the songs that exist in that timestep. Since we want to run large number of these simulations and compare the output in bulk, let’s simplify this to just be the median z value across all of the songs and plot it.

#simplify output to be median of medians
output <- sapply(1:length(output), function(x){median(output[[x]])})

As you can see, with these parameter values we get a nice steady increase in the median trill rate of all songs in the population over time. This is not realistic—we need to add a downward constraint!

Adding selective attrition

In songbirds, juveniles overlearn songs and then only produce a subset of them as adults through a process called selective attrition. In swamp sparrows, songs that are relatively difficult to produce are less likely to be produced in adulthood Podos et al. (2004). We can incorporate this into our model by making songs with higher z_max values less likely to be learned. To do this, we will modify the probability calculation in the sample function used when we generate our data table of new birds. Instead of prob = freq_table$freq it will be prob = freq_table$freq*((1/freq_table$z_max)^attrition). When attrition is 0 then the second term will have no impact on the sampling probabilities and learning will be random. As attrition increases, songs with higher z_max values will be less and less likely to be learned, in effect “hitting the brakes” on improvement in a way that reflects learning constraints. Let’s set attrition to 1 and see what happens.

#set parameter
attrition <- 1

#create output object
output <- list()

#for each timestep
for(i in 1:timesteps){
  #compile frequency table of songs in the population
  freq_table <- table(unlist(birds$rep))
  freq_table <- data.table::data.table(type = as.numeric(names(freq_table)), freq = as.numeric(freq_table), z_max = songs$z_max[as.numeric(names(freq_table))])

  #collect the median z values for each song in the population to output
  output[[i]] <- sapply(freq_table$type, function(x){median(sample_z(z_max = songs$z_max[x], alpha = songs$alpha[x], beta = songs$beta[x], N = N))})

  #new birds are born and learn song types proportional to their frequency in the population
  new_birds <- data.table::data.table(rep = lapply(1:(N*b_d_rate), function(x){sample(freq_table$type, rep_size, prob = freq_table$freq*((1/freq_table$z_max)^attrition))}))

  #new birds sampled to innovate with probability mu replace song types with another from the total pool of songs with probability mu
  to_innovate <- which(sample(c(TRUE, FALSE), N*b_d_rate, prob = c(mu, 1-mu), replace = TRUE))
  for(j in to_innovate){
    new_rep <- new_birds$rep[[j]]
    num_innovate <- rbinom(1, rep_size, mu)
    new_rep[sample(rep_size, num_innovate)] <- sample(total_types, num_innovate)
    new_birds$rep[[j]] <- new_rep
  }

  #improvement of song types occurs among new birds
  to_improve <- sort(unique(unlist(new_birds$rep)))
  for(j in to_improve){
    new_z_max <- max(sample_z(z_max = songs$z_max[j], alpha = songs$alpha[j], beta = songs$beta[j], N = N*b_d_rate))
    songs$z_max[j] <- new_z_max
  }

  #add new birds to entire population and then simulate mortality
  birds <- data.table::rbindlist(list(birds, new_birds))
  birds <- birds[-sample(N+(N*b_d_rate), N*b_d_rate), ]
}

#simplify output to be median of medians
output <- sapply(1:length(output), function(x){median(output[[x]])})

The red line above is the output of this new simulation that incorporates selective attrition biased by z_max.

Adding conformity

One last element we will add to our model is conformity, or the tendency to favor songs that are already very common in the population Lachlan et al. 2018. Adding this is quite simple. All we do is exponentiate the song frequencies in the probability calculation when we generate our data table of new birds. Instead of prob = freq_table$freq*((1/freq_table$z_max)^attrition) (the version that already includes attrition) it will be prob = (freq_table$freq^conformity)*((1/freq_table$z_max)^attrition). When conformity is 1 then nothing changes, but as it increase the more common songs will be more likely to be learned in each timestep. Let’s set conformity to 2 and see what happens.

#set parameter
attrition <- 1
conformity <- 2

#create output object
output <- list()

#for each timestep
for(i in 1:timesteps){
  #compile frequency table of songs in the population
  freq_table <- table(unlist(birds$rep))
  freq_table <- data.table::data.table(type = as.numeric(names(freq_table)), freq = as.numeric(freq_table), z_max = songs$z_max[as.numeric(names(freq_table))])

  #collect the median z values for each song in the population to output
  output[[i]] <- sapply(freq_table$type, function(x){median(sample_z(z_max = songs$z_max[x], alpha = songs$alpha[x], beta = songs$beta[x], N = N))})

  #new birds are born and learn song types proportional to their frequency in the population
  new_birds <- data.table::data.table(rep = lapply(1:(N*b_d_rate), function(x){sample(freq_table$type, rep_size, prob = (freq_table$freq^conformity)*((1/freq_table$z_max)^attrition))}))

  #new birds sampled to innovate with probability mu replace song types with another from the total pool of songs with probability mu
  to_innovate <- which(sample(c(TRUE, FALSE), N*b_d_rate, prob = c(mu, 1-mu), replace = TRUE))
  for(j in to_innovate){
    new_rep <- new_birds$rep[[j]]
    num_innovate <- rbinom(1, rep_size, mu)
    new_rep[sample(rep_size, num_innovate)] <- sample(total_types, num_innovate)
    new_birds$rep[[j]] <- new_rep
  }

  #improvement of song types occurs among new birds
  to_improve <- sort(unique(unlist(new_birds$rep)))
  for(j in to_improve){
    new_z_max <- max(sample_z(z_max = songs$z_max[j], alpha = songs$alpha[j], beta = songs$beta[j], N = N*b_d_rate))
    songs$z_max[j] <- new_z_max
  }

  #add new birds to entire population and then simulate mortality
  birds <- data.table::rbindlist(list(birds, new_birds))
  birds <- birds[-sample(N+(N*b_d_rate), N*b_d_rate), ]
}

#simplify output to be median of medians
output <- sapply(1:length(output), function(x){median(output[[x]])})

Running in bulk

Realistically, we would like to run many iterations of this model to compare the output of it under different conditions. Let’s package it up as a function so we can do that.

model <- function(N = 200, b_d_rate = 0.5, timesteps = 100,
                  total_types = 160, init_types = 20, rep_size = 10,
                  mu = 0.2, attrition = 0, conformity = 1, price_params = c(1, 0.4, 0.1, 0.01)){
  #create output object
  output <- list()
  
  #for each timestep
  for(i in 1:timesteps){
    #compile frequency table of songs in the population
    freq_table <- table(unlist(birds$rep))
    freq_table <- data.table::data.table(type = as.numeric(names(freq_table)), freq = as.numeric(freq_table), z_max = songs$z_max[as.numeric(names(freq_table))])
  
    #collect the median z values for each song in the population to output
    output[[i]] <- sapply(freq_table$type, function(x){median(sample_z(z_max = songs$z_max[x], alpha = songs$alpha[x], beta = songs$beta[x], N = N))})
  
    #new birds are born and learn song types proportional to their frequency in the population
    new_birds <- data.table::data.table(rep = lapply(1:(N*b_d_rate), function(x){sample(freq_table$type, rep_size, prob = (freq_table$freq^conformity)*((1/freq_table$z_max)^attrition))}))
  
    #new birds sampled to innovate with probability mu replace song types with another from the total pool of songs with probability mu
    to_innovate <- which(sample(c(TRUE, FALSE), N*b_d_rate, prob = c(mu, 1-mu), replace = TRUE))
    for(j in to_innovate){
      new_rep <- new_birds$rep[[j]]
      num_innovate <- rbinom(1, rep_size, mu)
      new_rep[sample(rep_size, num_innovate)] <- sample(total_types, num_innovate)
      new_birds$rep[[j]] <- new_rep
    }
  
    #improvement of song types occurs among new birds
    to_improve <- sort(unique(unlist(new_birds$rep)))
    for(j in to_improve){
      new_z_max <- max(sample_z(z_max = songs$z_max[j], alpha = songs$alpha[j], beta = songs$beta[j], N = N*b_d_rate))
      songs$z_max[j] <- new_z_max
    }
  
    #add new birds to entire population and then simulate mortality
    birds <- data.table::rbindlist(list(birds, new_birds))
    birds <- birds[-sample(N+(N*b_d_rate), N*b_d_rate), ]
  }
  
  #output result
  return(sapply(1:length(output), function(x){mean(output[[x]])}))
}

Now we can set how many iterations we want and run them in serial or in parallel across multiple cores (commented examples below). Let’s run three rounds of 20 iterations of the model: (1) with the default parameters, (2) with attrition set to 1, and (3) with conformity set to 2.

#set iterations
iters <- 20

#example in parallel
#output <- do.call(rbind, parallel::mclapply(1:iters, function(x){model()}, mc.cores = 8))

#example in serial
#output <- do.call(rbind, lapply(1:iters, function(x){model()}))

#run three rounds of the model
output_a <- do.call(rbind, parallel::mclapply(1:iters, function(x){model()}, mc.cores = 8))
output_b <- do.call(rbind, parallel::mclapply(1:iters, function(x){model(attrition = 1)}, mc.cores = 8))
output_c <- do.call(rbind, parallel::mclapply(1:iters, function(x){model(attrition = 1, conformity = 2)}, mc.cores = 8))

Plotting these is kind of complicated so here is the code. matplot is a great function that allows you to quickly plot a bunch of lines in a matrix. We provide matplot with a combined and transposed matrix of all of our model outputs. If we want we can also add the average value for each round of models at each timepoint.

#set opacity of the line colors
opacity <- 0.1

#generate vector of colors, one for each model result
colors <- c(rep(scales::alpha("black", opacity), nrow(output_a)),
            rep(scales::alpha("red", opacity), nrow(output_b)),
            rep(scales::alpha("blue", opacity), nrow(output_c)))

#adjust margins
par(mar = c(4.5, 4.5, 1, 1))

#plot lines
matplot(t(rbind(output_a, output_b, output_c)), type = "l", col = colors, lty = 1, xlab = "Timesteps", ylab = "Mean Syllable Quality")

#add average value lines
lines(colMeans(output_a), col = "black")
lines(colMeans(output_b), col = "red")
lines(colMeans(output_c), col = "blue")
